        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We have set the channel width to 0.164 km/s to specifically isolate any HDO absorption arising from the envelope.  This very high resolution will enable us to isolate broad disk absorption from narrow envelope absorption if both  disk/envelope are present.  We anticipate binning over channels to obtain higher signal to noise.  

We have added windows on a nearby D2O line with a 12 K lower-state energy, which may also be detected in absorption.  There is a nearby 13CO 8-7 which will also put interesting constraints on the temperature of the gas in the inner disk, which can be compared to the warm water vapor temperatures we are seeing with Herschel PACS. Finally, we have added one continuum band to get a sensitive continuum measurement and to help with the data/phase calibration.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>We do not aim to image the HDO, but rather take advantage of ALMA's frequency (Band 10) and sensitivity capabilities. We have requested the angular resolution of the second-most compact configuration for this spectral setting, 0.195'' at 893 GHz, where we will obtain the maximual continuum flux per beam while avoiding the C36-1 period where the atmospheric conditions are not favorable for high frequency studies.  If necessary, we will spatially integrate absorption detected over the full extent of the dust disk (1''x0.5'').  The dust semi-major axis is 1'' which is our LAS.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The continuum at 893 GHz is estimated from the SHARC II 350 micron (856 GHz) measurement of this disk reported in Andrews and Williams 2005. We assume a beta parameter of 0.7 measured for this source (Isella et al. 2009) to scale the SHARC II data to 893 GHz to obtain a disk-integrated flux of 2.73 Jy. In this experiment, the dust is the background source against which we will measure the absorption. The dust disk is 0.5x1.0'' in size (Isella et al. 2009), and so to estimate the continuum flux in the smaller beam, taking into account the increasing surface density with decreasing radius (i.e., the dust disk is not uniformly bright) we scale the flux by the desired beam size / disk size and predict a peak, centrally concentrated (Sigma~1/R) flux of 711 mJy. 

For the absorption line, as we describe in the proposal PDF, we expect the line center tau on the HDO (1_11-0_00) to be at least 0.54.  This implies an absorption feature with a depth of 300 mJy.  Thus we have set our sensitivity request to 100 mJy, given that the line is expected to be ~5 km/s and we have selected narrow channels to isolate any envelope emission, which improves the integrated signal to noise over the line by sqrt(5 km/s / 0.164 km/s) = 5.5, or a 17 sigma line-integrated detection. This is our most conservative estimate for a maximally broad line, and will be higher for even slightly narrower lines.  </prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
